# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: oracle-cloud-infrastructure
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] In computer networking, a **bare-metal server** or **physical server** is a computer server that is not a virtual machine, typically used by one consumer, or tenant, only.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] Each server offered for rental is a distinct physical piece of hardware that is a functional server on its own.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] They are not virtual servers running in multiple pieces of shared hardware.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] The term is used for distinguishing between servers that can host multiple tenants and which use virtualisation and cloud hosting.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] Unlike bare-metal servers, cloud servers are shared between multiple tenants.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] Each bare-metal server may run any amount of work for a user, or have multiple simultaneous users, but they are dedicated entirely to the entity who is renting them.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] Hypervisors provide some isolation between tenants but there can still be a noisy neighbour effect.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] If a physical server is multi-tenanted, peaks of load from one tenant may consume enough machine resources to temporarily affect other tenants.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] As the tenants are otherwise isolated, it is also hard to manage or load balance this.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] Bare-metal servers, and single tenancy, can avoid this.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] In addition, hypervisors provide weaker isolation and are much more risky from a security point-of-view compared to using separate machines.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] Attackers have always found vulnerabilities in the isolation software (such as hypervisors), covert channels are impractical to counter without physically separate machines, and shared hardware is vulnerable to defects in hardware protection mechanisms such as Rowhammer, Spectre, and Meltdown.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] As, once again, server costs are dropping as a proportion of total cost of ownership against their administration overhead, the classic solution of 'throwing hardware at the problem' becomes viable again.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] Infrastructure as a service, particularly through infrastructure as code, offers many advantages to make hosting conveniently manageable.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] Combining the features of both cloud hosting, and bare-metal servers, offers most of these, whilst still conveying the performance advantages.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] These cloud offerings are also called Bare-Metal-as-a-Service (BMaaS).
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] Some bare-metal cloud servers may run a hypervisor or containers, e.g., to simplify maintenance or provide additional layers of isolation.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] Note that the distinction between these services and the traditional dedicated server offerings is the user's ability to provision infrastructures composed out of multiple servers, a complex network and storage setup rather than servers in isolation.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] Both commercial and open-source platforms exist enabling companies to build their own private bare-Metal private clouds.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] BMaaS software typically takes over the lifecycle management of the equipment in a datacenter (compute, storage and network Switches, firewalls, load balancers and others).
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] It enables datacenter operators to offload much of the manual work typically associated with deploying hardware.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] It also reduces waste by simplifying reuse and increases security by implementing automatic cleanup and automatic segmentation between tenants at the network level.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] Increasingly BMaaS software is used internally to reduce the costs associated with lifecycle management of equipment for enterprises with large fleets of servers.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] BMaaS software aims to simplify hardware management and enable its as-a-service consumption.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] It handles primarily the layer below a hyper-converged or container-based solution.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] It often collaborates with the layers above through integrations such as the Kubernetes cluster autoscaler.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] BMaaS software has a similar objective to composable disaggregated infrastructure in that it aims to offer the user the ability to "compose" the desired compute unit defined as a set of resources (such as compute or storage).
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] The distinction is that the storage and compute need not be "dissagregated" (accessed from outside the server unit) as this often requires specialized hardware.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] Note that in some implementations, the storage component is external to the systems using iSCSI blurring the lines between BMaaS and composable infrastructure.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] This allows the user to choose the size and performance of the node's storage in a manner similar to classical virtualized Infrastructure as a Service offerings.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] This has the advantage of lower variability (snowflaking) in the hardware pool and the possibility of faster migration from one equipment to another in the event of hardware failure.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] As new workloads like augmented reality, mixed reality, connected cars, and telerobotics are gaining traction, demand for low-latency cloud services—and edge computing—are increasing.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] Bare Metal and the BMaaS automation software is used for edge cloud implementations, where large numbers of small data-centers need to be automated and then consumed as a service and where the service needs to offer the lowest latency possible.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] At one time, all servers were bare-metal servers.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] Servers were kept on-premises and often belonged to the organisation using and operating them.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] Operating systems developed very early on (early 1960s) to allow time-sharing.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] Single large computers, mainframes or minis, were commonly housed in centralised locations and their services shared through a bureau.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] The shift to cheap commodity PCs in the 1980s changed this as the market expanded, and most organisations, even the smallest, began to purchase or lease their own computers.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] Popular growth of the internet, and particularly the web, in the 1990s encouraged the practice of hosting in data centres, where many customers shared the facilities of single servers.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] Small web servers at this time often cost more for their connectivity than their hardware cost, encouraging this centralisation.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] HTTP 1.1's ability for virtual hosting also made it easy to co-host many web sites on the same server.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] From around 2000, or 2005 in commercially practical terms, interest grew in the use of virtual servers and then cloud hosting, where infrastructure as a service made the computing *service* the fungible commodity, rather than the server hardware.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] Hypervisors were developed which could offer many virtual machines hosted on larger physical servers.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/bare-metal-server] One of the forefathers of bare metal provisioning is Cobbler that appeared in the 1990s and was using the Preboot Execution Environment (PXE) protocol.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/infrastructure-as-a-service] IaaS clouds often offer additional resources such as a virtual-machine disk-image library, raw block storage, file or object storage, firewalls, load balancers, IP addresses, virtual local area networks (VLANs), and software bundles.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/infrastructure-as-a-service] IaaS-cloud providers supply resources on-demand from the large pools of equipment installed in data centers.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/infrastructure-as-a-service] For wide-area connectivity, customers can use either the Internet or carrier clouds (dedicated virtual private networks, VPNs).
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/infrastructure-as-a-service] To deploy their applications, users install operating-system images and the application software on the cloud infrastructure.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/infrastructure-as-a-service] Users patch and maintain the operating systems.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/infrastructure-as-a-service] IaaS services are typically billed as a utility: cost reflects the amount of resources allocated or consumed.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/infrastructure-as-a-service] Typically, IaaS involves the use of a cloud orchestration technology such as OpenStack, Apache CloudStack, or OpenNebula.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/infrastructure-as-a-service] It manages the creation of a virtual machine (VM) and decides on the hypervisor (i.e. physical host) in order to start it.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/infrastructure-as-a-service] A hypervisor runs virtual machines (VMs) as guests.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/infrastructure-as-a-service] Pools of hypervisors in the cloud operational system can support large numbers of virtual machines and the ability to scale services up and down according to demand by customers.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/infrastructure-as-a-service] Hypervisors include Xen, Oracle VirtualBox, Oracle VM, KVM, VMware ESX/ESXi, or Microsoft Hyper-V.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/infrastructure-as-a-service] It also enables VM migration between hosts, allocates storage volumes, and attaches them to VMs that track usage information for billing.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/infrastructure-as-a-service] An alternative to hypervisors is Linux containers, which run in isolated partitions of a Linux kernel that runs directly on the physical hardware.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/infrastructure-as-a-service] Containers are isolated, secured and managed using Linux cgroups and namespaces.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/infrastructure-as-a-service] Containerisation offers higher performance than virtualization because there is no hypervisor overhead.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/infrastructure-as-a-service] The global IaaS market is projected to reach a value of $411.9 billion by 2030, expanding at a compound annual growth rate (CAGR) of 22.6% from 2023 to 2030.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/infrastructure-as-a-service] This growth is primarily driven by the adoption of cloud-based infrastructure within the Banking, Financial Services, and Insurance (BFSI) sector, which employs these technologies to enhance scalability and reduce operational costs.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/infrastructure-as-a-service] The UK Government encourages departments to use public cloud solutions as a first option.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/infrastructure-as-a-service] IaaS is in use within the UK Government but the technology community within government recommends consideration of Platform as a Service (PaaS) in cases where a department may not have IaaS skills and management capacity.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-cloud] Oracle Cloud provides infrastructure as a service (IaaS), platform as a service (PaaS), software as a service (SaaS), and data as a service (DaaS).
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-cloud] These services are used to build, deploy, integrate, and extend applications in the cloud.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-cloud] Oracle's cloud infrastructure was made generally available (GA) on October 20, 2016 under the name "Oracle Bare Metal Cloud Services".
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-cloud] Oracle Bare Metal Cloud Services was rebranded as Oracle Cloud Infrastructure in 2018 and dubbed Oracle's "Generation 2 Cloud" at Oracle OpenWorld 2018.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-cloud] In 2016, Oracle acquired Dyn, an internet infrastructure company.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-cloud] On May 16, 2018 Oracle announced that it had acquired DataScience.com, a privately held cloud workspace platform for data science projects and workloads.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-cloud] In April 2020, Oracle became the cloud infrastructure provider for Zoom, an online and video meeting platform.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-cloud] The same month, Nissan announced its migration to Oracle Cloud for its high-performance computing (HPC) workloads used for simulating the structural impacts of a car design.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-cloud] Xerox announced a partnership with Oracle Cloud in 2021, where Xerox will use Oracle's cloud-computing capabilities within its business incubator.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-cloud] Oracle provides SaaS applications also known as Oracle Cloud Applications.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-cloud] These applications are offered across a variety of products, industrial sectors with various deployment options to adhere to compliance standards.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-cloud] The below list mentions Oracle Cloud Applications provided by Oracle Corporation.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-cloud] On July 28, 2016 Oracle bought NetSuite, the very first cloud company, for $9.3 billion.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-cloud] This platform is known as the Oracle Data Cloud.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-cloud] This platform aggregates and analyzes consumer data powered by Oracle ID Graph across channels and devices to create cross-channel consumer understanding.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-cloud] Oracle Cloud is available in 44 regions as of July 2023, including North America, South America, UK, European Union, Middle East, Africa, India, Australia, Korea, and Japan.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-cloud] Oracle's public and government cloud is offered through a global network of Oracle-managed data centers, connected by an Oracle-managed backbone network.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-cloud] Oracle's Exadata Cloud at Customer leverages this network for control plane services.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-cloud] Oracle deploys their cloud in Regions, typically with two geographically distributed regions in each country for disaster resiliency with data sovereignty.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-cloud] Inside each Region are at least one fault-independent Availability Domain and three fault-tolerant Fault Domains per Availability Domain.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-cloud] Each Availability Domains contains an independent data center with power, thermal, and network isolation.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-cloud] Oracle Cloud hosts customer-accessible cloud infrastructure and platform services, as well as end-user accessible software as a service from these cloud regions.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] The company sells database software (particularly the Oracle Database), enterprise applications, and cloud infrastructure and hardware.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Oracle's core application software is a suite of enterprise software products, including enterprise resource planning (ERP), human capital management (HCM), customer experience (CX) and supply chain management (SCM) software.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Larry Ellison, Bob Miner, and Ed Oates co-founded Oracle on June 16, 1977, in Santa Clara, California, as **Software Development Laboratories** (**SDL**).
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Beginning as consultants with a background in large-scale memory after a project for Ampex, Ellison took inspiration from the 1970 paper written by Edgar F.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Codd on relational database management systems (RDBMS) named "A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks." He heard about the IBM System R database from an article in an IBM research journal provided by Oates.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Ellison wanted to make Oracle's product compatible with System R, but failed to do so as IBM kept the error codes for its DBMS a secret.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] SDL changed its name to **Relational Software, Inc** (**RSI**) in 1979, then again to **Oracle Systems Corporation** in 1983, to align itself more closely with its flagship product Oracle Database.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] The name also drew from the codename of a 1977 project for the Central Intelligence Agency, Oracle's first customer; the company received permission to use the code name for the new product.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Miner served as a senior programmer, and Oates also worked in development.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] The three founders decided that Ellison was the worst programmer so he became the salesman.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Understanding both customers and technology, Ellison designed database tables that he used to demonstrate the power of SQL to customers.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] By February 1983 the *Rosen Electronics Letter* said that Oracle was "the most comprehensive offering we've seen" among databases, with good marketing and a substantial installed base encouraging developers to write software for it.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] The newsletter said that revenue in fiscal 1983 would be about $8 million and would double in 1984.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] On March 12, 1986, the company had its initial public offering.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In 1989, Oracle moved its world headquarters to the Redwood Shores neighborhood of Redwood City, California, though its campus was not completed until 1995.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] The company hired so many from top universities that Humphries compared it to "Cargill buying crops".
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Some new employees worked as receptionists or distributed coffee until more suitable positions became available.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Oracle in the late 1980s began selling enterprise software running on the database, starting with financial software, then manufacturing.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Many at Oracle wanted to discontinue applications; the first several versions were weak, they competed with the company's independent software vendors and value-added reseller partners, and applications were never profitable for Oracle until after 2000.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Selling them (and acquiring vendors such as JD Edwards and PeopleSoft, the latter being the second hostile takeover in the history of software) nonetheless allowed Oracle to compete with SAP; by the mid-2000s it was the world's largest enterprise software vendor.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In 1995, Oracle Systems Corporation changed its name to **Oracle Corporation**, officially named Oracle, but is sometimes referred to as Oracle Corporation, the name of the holding company.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In 2010, Oracle launched Fusion Applications to unify the features and technologies of acquisitions PeopleSoft, Siebel Systems, and JD Edwards, into a single suite.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] On July 15, 2013, Oracle transferred its stock listing from Nasdaq to the New York Stock Exchange.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] At the time, it was the largest-ever U.S. market transfer.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In 2018, Oracle opened a new office in the neighboorhod of East Riverside in southeast Austin, Texas.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In December 2020, Oracle announced that it was moving its world headquarters from Redwood Shores to Austin, Texas.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In an effort to compete with Amazon Web Services and its products, Oracle announced in 2019 it was partnering with former rival Microsoft.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] The alliance claimed that Oracle Cloud and Microsoft Azure would be directly connected, allowing customers of each to store data on both cloud computing platforms and run software on either Oracle or Azure.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Some saw this not only as an attempt to compete with Amazon but also with Google and Salesforce, which acquired Looker and Tableau Software, respectively.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In 2023, Oracle and Microsoft expanded their partnership to deliver Oracle database services on Oracle Cloud Infrastructure running inside Microsoft Azure.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] A year later, Oracle announced similar partnerships with Amazon Web Services and Google Cloud, making the Oracle database available in all four major hyperscaler providers.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In December 2021, Oracle announced the acquisition of Cerner, a health information technology company.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] The acquisition of Cerner was completed on June 8, 2022, for US$28.3 billion in cash.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Also in December 2021, Oracle announced the acquisition of Federos, an artificial intelligence (AI) and automation tools company for network performance.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In February 2023, the company announced it was going to invest $1.5 billion into the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia, including opening a data center in the country's capital, Riyadh.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In April 2024, Oracle announced it was moving its world headquarters from Austin to a new complex in Nashville, Tennessee.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In June 2024, Oracle announced a $1 billion investment in Spain to enhance artificial intelligence and cloud computing.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] This investment will create a new cloud region in Madrid in partnership with Telefónica.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] The goal is to help Spanish businesses and the public sector with digital transformation and to meet European Union regulations.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] The same year, the company announced investments in Japan and Malaysia for US$8 billion and US$6.5 billion, respectively.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In January 2025, President Donald Trump announced Stargate, a joint venture by Oracle, OpenAI, SoftBank and investment firm MGX to invest $500 billion over four years in artificial intelligence infrastructure in the US.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Also in 2025, the company announced additional investments in the United Kingdom, Germany and the Netherlands for US$5 billion and US$3 billion, respectively.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In September 2025, Oracle announced it was promoting Clay Magouyrk, president of cloud infrastructure, and Mike Sicilia, president of industries, to become co-CEOs.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] They replaced Safra Catz, who held the position for 11 years, and transitioned to a new role as executive vice chair.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In January 2026, social media platform TikTok announced it finalized a deal to change ownership of its U.S. operations, with Oracle, MGX and private equity firm Silver Lake each owning a 15% stake in the venture, while ByteDance retained a 19.9% stake.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] As of March 2026, Oracles TikTok stake was worth an estimated ~$2B.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In March 2026, Oracle signed a voluntary "ratepayer protection pledge" where companies pledge to build or buy energy needed to power data centers at a different rate to regular consumers, allowing them to keep utility bills down substantially.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In April 2026, it was reported that Oracle laid off nearly 12,000 staff in India, according to the impacted employees.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] The company was believed to be planning another mass layoff round within a month.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] For the second quarter of fiscal year 2026 (ending November 2025), Oracle reported total revenue of $14.1 billion, with cloud infrastructure (IaaS) revenue growing 68% year-over-year to $4.1 billion.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Total remaining performance obligations surged to $130 billion, reflecting strong demand for AI infrastructure capacity.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Oracle provides cloud infrastructure, AI services, database and database management software, enterprise applications, analytics, and developer tools that help businesses manage their data, operations, and IT environments.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Oracle provides software applications, such as integrated enterprise software applications, Oracle Fusion Cloud Applications, human capital management (HCM), customer relationship management (CRM), and supply chain management (SCM).
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] The Oracle Database was released in 2004 as 10g.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Subsequently, the product was released several times, with the newest issue released as 12c in 2018.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Oracle released its Autonomous Database in 2018, Oracle Database 23ai in 2024, and issued its newest release Oracle AI Database 26ai in 2025.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Oracle Fusion Middleware is a family of middleware software products, including application server, system integration, business process management (BPM), user interaction, content management, identity management and business intelligence (BI) products.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Oracle Applications, software sold by Oracle based on its own database, first appeared in the late 1980s.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Oracle Enterprise Manager (OEM) is a web-based monitoring and management tool for Oracle products (and for some third-party software), including database management, middleware management, application management, hardware and virtualization management and cloud management.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] The Primavera products of Oracle's Construction & Engineering Global Business Unit (CEGBU) consist of project-management software.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Oracle Corporation develops and supports two operating systems: Oracle Solaris and Oracle Linux.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Oracle Cloud is a cloud computing service offered by Oracle Corporation providing servers, storage, network, applications and services through a global network of Oracle Corporation managed data centers.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] The company allows these services to be provisioned on demand over the Internet.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Oracle Cloud provides Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), Software as a Service (SaaS) and Data as a Service (DaaS).
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] These services are used to build, deploy, integrate and extend applications in the cloud.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Oracle has continued to make updates to its generative AI service, which is built and supported on Oracle Cloud Infrastructure and large language models (LLM) from Cohere as of 2023, Meta's Llama as of 2024, and xAI's Grok 3 as of 2025.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] The company has also been working to integrate generative AI into its other services.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In April 2025, Oracle incorporated HeatWave GenAI into its database.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In September 2025, Oracle and OpenAI signed a $300 billion contract for 4.5 gigawatts of power capacity over five years.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In October 2025, Oracle and Microsoft announced a partnership to enhance supply chain efficiency and responsiveness for manufacturers.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] It was also announced that Oracle will offer cloud services using Advanced Micro Devices' upcoming MI450 artificial intelligence chips.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] OPERA Cloud is a property management software (PMS) positioned under Oracle Hospitality.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] It's available across 236 countries and territories.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In 2026, IHG Hotels & Resorts onboarded OPERA Cloud as its official PMS.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In 2025, Accor onboarded it as its official PMS, moving away from Mews (software).
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In 2023, it was a market leader among PMSs.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In 1990, Oracle laid off 10% (about 400 people) of its work force because of accounting errors.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] This crisis came about because of Oracle's "up-front" marketing strategy, in which sales people urged potential customers to buy the largest possible amount of software all at once.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] The sales people then booked the value of future license sales in the current quarter, thereby increasing their bonuses.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] This became a problem when the future sales subsequently failed to materialize.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Oracle eventually had to restate its earnings twice, and also settled (out of court) class-action lawsuits arising from its having overstated its earnings.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Ellison stated in 1992 that Oracle had made "an incredible business mistake".
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Humphries described the cause ("building for years") as a combination of technical problems that benefited rivals, and the sales force using side letters and other improper tactics to meet the company's longstanding goal of doubling revenue each year.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Ellison hired ("bring in adults", Jerry Held said) new executives Jeff Henley and Raymond J.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Lane, who helped the company recover from what Ken Jacobs later described as a "near death experience", in which Oracle required an investment from a Japanese steel company to meet payroll.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] The relational database industry was unusually concentrated.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Besides being headquartered near each other in the San Francisco Bay area, database technology experts attended the same universities and served on the same standards committees (with Jim Gray serving as neutral arbiter as companies tried to get competing proposals enacted).
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Sales and marketing people were both fierce rivals and often moved between the companies, even as engineers socialized with each other.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] The smaller, later-founded database vendors viewed Oracle as their top enemy, with Bob MacDonald of Informix Software calling Oracle "the evil empire", while Humphries described his company as "the Klingons of" the bay.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Held later described his company's philosophy as "it's not good enough for Oracle to win.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] It was important for somebody else to lose".
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Ingres was its first major competitor; Oracle's strategy of focusing on one opponent at a time.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Even publicly complimenting other rivals "to take the pressure off", Held said, while effective, caused it to neglect Sybase as a threat.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Conversely, when Sybase had technical problems "it was: how do you put every ounce of product marketing, sales effort and focus on that".
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] IBM's endorsement of SQL in Db2 in the early 1980s benefited Oracle and forced rivals like Ingres and Informix Corporation to adopt SQL to compete.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Oracle acknowledged IBM as the standard while emphasizing its own superiority, touting "total IBM SQL compatibility" while IBM's software ran "*only on IBM mainframes*".
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] By the mid-1980s the company described its database as "the last DBMS", bragging that Oracle now had larger database revenue than dBASE maker Ashton-Tate, and stating that Microsoft, Ashton-Tate, and Sybase's planned Microsoft SQL Server "jumped on Oracle's SQL bandwagon".
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] MacDonald credited Oracle with "being marketing oriented before any of the competitors ... pushing the envelope on selling the future way ahead of the rest of us".
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Stu Schuster of Sybase said "Larry taught us a lot about marketing".
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] While other database companies' brochures emphasized technical features, Oracle advertisements showed an Oracle jet fighter shooting down Ashton-Tate and Borland biplanes; dBASE, IBM, and Db2 were among the many competitors Oracle marketing criticized by name.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Conversely, another Oracle ad quoted Microsoft's Bill Gates, Sun's Scott McNealy, Hewlett-Packard's John A.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Young, and Apple Computer's John Sculley as agreeing with Ellison on Oracle's database breakthroughs.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Larry Rowe of Ingres said "you could never come up with a strategy to beat Oracle because whatever you said today, two days later Ellison was saying it with more marketing dollars".
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Schuster and Held recalled "a not very pleasant environment because it was so directly competitive".
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Even IBM participated in the "billboard wars".
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] By 1995 Oracle had 44% of the $2.4 billion relational database market; Sybase had 17% and Informix had 16%.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] By 1996 Informix, after acquiring Illustra, became Oracle's most important rival.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] The intense war between Informix CEO Phil White and Ellison made front-page news in Silicon Valley for three years.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Informix claimed that Oracle had hired away Informix engineers to disclose important trade secrets about an upcoming product.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Informix finally dropped its lawsuit against Oracle in 1997.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In November 2005, a book detailing the war between Oracle and Informix was published, titled *The Real Story of Informix Software and Phil White*.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] It gave a detailed chronology of the battle of Informix against Oracle, and how Informix Software's CEO Phil White landed in jail because of his obsession with overtaking Ellison.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Oracle has competed for new database licenses on UNIX, GNU, and Windows operating systems primarily against IBM's Db2 and Microsoft SQL Server.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In 2004, Oracle's sales grew at a rate of 14.5% to $6.2 billion, giving it 41.3% and the top share of the relational-database market (*InformationWeek* – March 2005), with market share estimated at up to 44.6% in 2005 by some sources.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Oracle Corporation's main competitors in the database arena remain IBM Db2 and Microsoft SQL Server, and to a lesser extent Sybase and Teradata, with free databases such as PostgreSQL and MySQL also having a significant share of the market.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] EnterpriseDB, based on PostgreSQL, has recently made inroads by proclaiming that its product delivers Oracle-compatible SQL and procedural language features at a much lower price-point.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Oracle's main competitors in the database market include IBM and Microsoft, and in enterprise applications, SAP.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] On March 22, 2007, Oracle sued SAP, accusing it of fraud and unfair competition.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In the market for business intelligence software, many other software companies, both small and large, have successfully competed in quality with Oracle and SAP products.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Business intelligence vendors can be categorized into the "big four" consolidated BI firms such as Oracle, who has entered BI market through a recent trend of acquisitions (including Hyperion Solutions), and the independent "pure play" vendors such as MicroStrategy, Actuate, and SAS.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Oracle Financials was ranked in the Top 20 Most Popular Accounting Software Infographic by Capterra in 2014, beating out SAP and a number of its other competitors.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] From 1988, Oracle Corporation and the German company SAP AG had a decade-long history of cooperation, beginning with the integration of SAP's R/3 enterprise application suite with Oracle's relational database products.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Despite the SAP partnership with Microsoft, and the increasing integration of SAP applications with Microsoft products (such as Microsoft SQL Server, a competitor to Oracle Database), Oracle and SAP continue their cooperation.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] According to Oracle Corporation, the majority of SAP's customers use Oracle databases.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In 2004, Oracle began to increase its interest in the enterprise-applications market (in 1989, Oracle had already released Oracle Financials).
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] A series of acquisitions by Oracle Corporation began, most notably with those of PeopleSoft, Siebel Systems, and Hyperion.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] SAP recognized that Oracle had started to become a competitor in a market where SAP had the leadership, and saw an opportunity to lure in customers from those companies that Oracle Corporation had acquired.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] SAP would offer those customers special discounts on the licenses for its enterprise applications.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Oracle and SAP (the latter through its recently acquired subsidiary TomorrowNow) competed in the third-party enterprise software maintenance and support market.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] On March 22, 2007, Oracle filed a lawsuit against SAP.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] SAP AG Oracle alleged that TomorrowNow, which provides discount support for legacy Oracle product lines, used the accounts of former Oracle customers to systematically download patches and support documents from Oracle's website and to appropriate them for SAP's use.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Some analysts have suggested the suit could form part of a strategy by Oracle Corporation to decrease competition with SAP in the market for third-party enterprise software maintenance and support.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] On July 3, 2007, SAP admitted that TomorrowNow employees had made "inappropriate downloads" from the Oracle support website.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] However, it claims that SAP personnel and SAP customers had no access to Oracle intellectual property via TomorrowNow.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] SAP's CEO Henning Kagermann stated that "Even a single inappropriate download is unacceptable from my perspective.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] We regret very much that this occurred." Additionally, SAP announced that it had "instituted changes" in TomorrowNow's operational oversight.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] On November 23, 2010, a U.S. district court jury in Oakland, California, found that SAP AG must pay Oracle Corp $1.3 billion for copyright infringement, awarding damages that could be the largest-ever for copyright infringement.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] While admitting liability, SAP estimated the damages at no more than $40 million, while Oracle claimed that they are at least $1.65 billion.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] The awarded amount is one of the 10 or 20 largest jury verdicts in U.S. legal history.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] SAP said it was disappointed by the verdict and might appeal.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] On September 1, 2011, a federal judge overturned the judgment and offered a reduced amount or a new trial, calling Oracle's original award "grossly" excessive.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] On August 3, 2012, SAP and Oracle agreed on a judgment for $306 million in damages, pending approval from the U.S. district court judge, "to save time and expense of [a] new trial".
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] After the accord has been approved, Oracle can ask a federal appeals court to reinstate the earlier jury verdict.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In addition to the damages payment, SAP has already paid Oracle $120 million for its legal fees.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] 82 in the 2018 Fortune 500 list of the largest United States corporations by total revenue.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] According to Bloomberg, Oracle's CEO-to-employee pay ratio is 1,205:1.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Oracle is one of the approved employers of ACCA and the median employee compensation rate was $89,887.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In 2000, Oracle attracted attention from the computer industry and the press after hiring private investigators to uncover unfavorable information from organizations sympathetic to rival Microsoft.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] During the investigation, Oracle was accused of attempting to purchase trash from a janitor at the Association for Competitive Technology.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] This resulted in an antitrust trial against Microsoft.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] The Chairman of Oracle Corporation, Larry Ellison, defended his company's hiring of an East Coast detective agency, calling the snooping a "public service".
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] The investigation reportedly included a $1,200 offer to janitors at the Association for Competitive Technology to look through Microsoft's trash.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In 2002, Oracle Corporation marketed many of its products using the slogan "Can't break it, can't break in", or "Unbreakable".
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] However, two weeks after its introduction, David Litchfield, Alexander Kornbrust, Cesar Cerrudo and others demonstrated a suite of successful attacks against Oracle products.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Oracle Corporation's chief security officer Mary Ann Davidson said that, rather than representing a literal claim of Oracle's products' impregnability, she saw the campaign in the context of fourteen independent security evaluations that Oracle Corporation's database server had passed.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In 2004, then-United States Attorney General John Ashcroft sued Oracle Corporation to prevent it from acquiring a multibillion-dollar intelligence contract.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] After Ashcroft's resignation from government, he founded a lobbying firm, The Ashcroft Group, which Oracle hired in 2005.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] With the group's help, Oracle went on to acquire the contract.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Oracle Corporation was awarded a contract by the State of Oregon's Oregon Health Authority (OHA) to develop Cover Oregon, the state's healthcare exchange website, as part of the U.S.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] When the site tried to go live on October 1, 2013, it failed, and registrations had to be taken using paper applications until the site could be fixed.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In August 2014, Oracle Corporation sued Cover Oregon for breach of contract, and then later that month the state of Oregon sued Oracle Corporation, in a civil complaint for breach of contract, fraud, filing false claims and "racketeering".
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In September 2016, the two sides reached a settlement valued at over $100 million to the state, and a six-year agreement for Oracle to continue modernizing state software and IT.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In August 2022, a class action lawsuit was filed against Oracle by the law firm Lieff Cabraser.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] The lawsuit alleged that Oracle engaged in "deliberate and purposeful surveillance of the general population via their digital and online existence", specifically focusing on Oracle operating a surveillance machine that tracked and recorded personal data in real-time.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] The litigants alleged that through such surveillance, the company violated the Federal Electronic Communications Privacy Act, California's state constitution, the California Invasion of Privacy Act, competition law, and California Common Law.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] The lawsuit was settled in July 2024 for $115 million.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Between 2011 and 2024, Oracle was investigated for engaging in bribery practices that violated the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act across its subsidiaries in South Africa, India, Turkey, and the United Arab Emirates.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In all instances, the company settled with the United States Securities and Exchange Commission.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Following the beginning of the Gaza war in 2023, Oracle's top executives, including Safra Catz and Larry Ellison, publicly aligned the company with Israel's military operations.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] They issued statements of solidarity, paid double salaries to Israeli employees, and donated to organizations connected to Israel's wartime response.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In 2024, Catz said to Israeli business news outlet CTech, "For employees, it's clear: if you're not for America or Israel, don't work here".
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In 2025, *The Intercept* spoke with Oracle employees who supported Palestine, but were afraid to speak out in their workplace.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Sixty-eight Oracle employees signed an open letter criticizing the company's ties to Israel.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] On July 29, 2010, the United States Department of Justice (DoJ) filed suit against Oracle Corporation alleging fraud.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] The lawsuit argues that the government received deals inferior to those Oracle gave to its commercial clients.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] The DoJ added its heft to an already existing whistleblower lawsuit filed by Paul Frascella, who was once senior director of contract services at Oracle.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Oracle, the plaintiff, acquired ownership of the Java computer programming language when it acquired Sun Microsystems in January 2010.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] The Java software includes sets of pre-developed software code to allow programs and apps to accomplish common tasks in a consistent manner.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] The pre-developed code is organized into separate "packages" which each contain a set of "classes".
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Each class contains numerous methods, which instruct a program or app to do a certain task.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Software developers "became accustomed to using Java's designations at the package, class, and method level".
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Oracle and Google (the defendant) tried to negotiate an agreement for Oracle to license Java to Google, which would have allowed Google to use Java in developing programs for mobile devices using the Android operating system.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] However, the two companies never reached an agreement.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] After negotiations failed, Google created its own programming platform, which was based on Java, and contained 37 copied Java packages as well as new packages developed by Google.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] On June 15, 2011, HP filed a lawsuit in California Superior Court in Santa Clara, claiming that Oracle had breached an agreement to support the Itanium microprocessor used in HP's high-end enterprise servers.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Oracle called the lawsuit "an abuse of the judicial process" and said that had it known SAP's Léo Apotheker was about to be hired as HP's new CEO, any support for HP's Itanium servers would not have been implied.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] On August 1, 2012, a California judge said in a tentative ruling that Oracle must continue porting its software at no cost until HP discontinues its sales of Itanium-based servers.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] HP was awarded $3 billion in damages against Oracle in 2016.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] HP argued Oracle's canceling support damaged HP's Itanium server brand.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Oracle had announced that it would appeal both the decision and damages, but the decision stayed.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] On April 20, 2012, the US General Services Administration banned Oracle from the most popular portal for bidding on GSA contracts for undisclosed reasons.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Oracle has previously used this portal for around four hundred million dollars a year in revenue.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In 2011, Oracle settled with the General Services Administration for $199.5 million in a lawsuit filed under the False Claims Act.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In January 2010, Oracle completed its acquisition of Sun Microsystems, valued at more than $7 billion, a move that transformed Oracle from solely a software company to a manufacturer of both software and hardware.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] The acquisition was delayed for several months by the European Commission because of concerns about MySQL, but was unconditionally approved in the end.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] State Department Embassy cables were leaked to WikiLeaks.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] One cable revealed that the U.S. pressured the E.U. to allow Oracle to acquire Sun.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] The Sun acquisition was closely watched by free software users and some companies, due to the fear that Oracle might end Sun's traditional support of free projects.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Since the acquisition, Oracle has discontinued OpenSolaris and StarOffice, and sued Google over the Java patents Oracle acquired from Sun.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] On December 20, 2021, Oracle announced that it agreed to acquire Cerner Corporation (now *Oracle Health* and *Oracle Life Sciences*) for approximately US$28.3 billion, creating a dedicated Industry Business Unit within the company.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Cerner is the largest international supplier of health information technology, such as electronic health records (EHR), revenue cycle solutions, and biomedical device integration platforms, and has its headquarters in Kansas City, Missouri, US.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] The deal closed in early July 2022 after receiving final approval from European regulators, making it Oracle's largest acquisition and one of the largest in corporate history.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Oracle's purchase of Cerner was part of an effort to introduce Oracle products into the healthcare market, particularly in the United States although Oracle plans to expand Cerner's global operations.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In September 2024, Oracle announced new investments and the release of Oracle Clinical Digital Assistant, a generative AI system that automatically creates consultation documentation and proposes orders.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In March 2025, a threat actor claimed to have stolen 6 million data records from Oracle Health (formerly Cerner).
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Oracle claimed that its Oracle Cloud Infrastructure was not breached and that no customer data from it was exposed.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Some legacy Cerner servers experienced unauthorized access, but Oracle has not confirmed the scale of impact.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In April 2025, the Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency (CISA) issued a warning to Oracle customers to secure their environments.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] On September 13, 2020, Bloomberg News reported that Oracle won a bidding war with other U.S.-based companies to take over social media company TikTok's operations in the United States following the company's pressure to forcibly be shut down by the Trump administration.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Oracle was described as a "trusted tech partner" by TikTok.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] On September 19, 2020, the Trump administration approved of the sale of TikTok's US operations to Oracle "[delaying] — by one week — restrictions that were originally to take effect" on September 20 as indicated by the United States Department of Commerce.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] As September 25, 2025, TikTok was bought by Silver Lake and Abu Dhabi's MGX.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Oracle will own 45% of the app in the US, and ByteDance 35% after delays with the ban for the 4th time.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Oracle will store data of US TikTok users on its cloud computers, and it will be involved in the new TikTok spinoff's cybersecurity.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Oracle partnered with the arms company Anduril Industries to provide their Lattice military software platform to the governments of United States, United Kingdom and Australia.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Oracle Corporation's world headquarters are located in Austin, Texas.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In April 2024, Oracle announced plans to build its largest office hub, with 8,500 jobs, in Nashville, Tennessee.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Oracle has a large office complex located on the San Francisco Peninsula in the Redwood Shores area of Redwood City.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] This complex was home to Oracle world headquarters from 1989 to 2020.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] It is located on the former site of Marine World/Africa USA, which moved from Redwood Shores to Vallejo in 1986.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Oracle Corporation originally leased two buildings on the Oracle Parkway site, moving its finance and administration departments from the corporation's former headquarters on Davis Drive, Belmont, California.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Eventually, Oracle purchased the complex and constructed four additional buildings.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] The distinctive Oracle Parkway buildings, nicknamed the Emerald City, served as sets for the futuristic headquarters of the fictional company "NorthAm Robotics" in the Robin Williams film *Bicentennial Man* (1999).
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] The campus also represented the headquarters of Cyberdyne Systems in the movie *Terminator Genisys* (2015).
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Oracle Corporation operates in multiple markets and has acquired many companies to help it do so.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In some cases these companies became the starting points for global business units (GBUs) targeting particular vertical markets.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In 1994 and 1995, Oracle sponsored Benetton Formula.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] From 2001 to 2021, Sean Tucker's stunt biplane was sponsored by Oracle and performed frequently at air shows around the US.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In October 2006, the Golden State Warriors and the Oracle Corporation announced a 10-year agreement in which the Oakland Arena would become known as the Oracle Arena.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] The agreement ended after the 2018–2019 NBA season when the Warriors relocated to the Chase Center in San Francisco.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] In January 2019, the San Francisco Giants entered into a 20-year agreement to rename its stadium Oracle Park.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] Larry Ellison's sailing team competes as Oracle Team USA.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] The team won the America's Cup twice, in 2010 (as BMW Oracle Racing) and in 2013, despite being penalized for cheating.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-corporation] From the 2022 Formula One season, Oracle signed a five-year deal worth $500 million to become title sponsors of Red Bull Racing, after already being a sponsor effective from the 2021 season.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-database] It is commonly used for online transaction processing (OLTP), data warehousing (DW), and mixed database workloads.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-database] As a converged database, it supports multiple data models within a single engine, including relational, JSON document, XML, spatial, graph, text, and vector data, all queryable through SQL.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-database] Oracle Database runs on-premises, on Oracle engineered systems such as Oracle Exadata, on Oracle Cloud Infrastructure, and as a managed Autonomous Database service.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-database] It is also offered inside Microsoft Azure, Google Cloud, and Amazon Web Services data centers through Oracle's multicloud offerings.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-database] The current long-term release is Oracle AI Database 26ai, which was introduced in October 2025.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-database] Larry Ellison and his two friends and former co-workers, Bob Miner and Ed Oates, started a consultancy called Software Development Laboritories (SDL) in 1977, later Oracle Corporation.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-database] SDL developed the original version of the Oracle software.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-database] The name *Oracle* comes from the code-name of a Central Intelligence Agency-funded project Ellison has worked on while formerly employed by Ampex; the CIA was Oracle's first customer, and allowed the company to use the code name for the new product.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-database] Ellison wanted his database to be compatible with IBM System R, but that company's Don Chamberlin declined to release its error codes.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-database] By 1985 Oracle advertised, however, that "Programs written for SQL/DS or DB2 will run unmodified" on the many non-IBM mainframes, minicomputers, and microcomputers its database supported "Because all versions of ORACLE *are* identical".
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-database] Oracle Corporation held its initial public offering on March 12, 1986.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-database] The company grew rapidly during the 1980s, though a financial setback in 1990 led to its first quarterly loss and significant layoffs before the business recovered.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-database] Oracle7, released in 1992, matured the product into a leading enterprise relational database management system, adding persistent PL/SQL stored procedures and triggers, a cost-based query optimizer, and improved administration tools.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-database] Oracle Database 12c (2013) introduced the multitenant architecture and the In-Memory Column Store, with "c" denoting "cloud".
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-database] In 2017 Oracle announced Oracle Autonomous Database, a self-managing cloud service, with the first services becoming available in 2018.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-database] Beyond the on-premises editions, Oracle Autonomous Database automates provisioning, tuning, patching, and scaling and is offered in data-warehousing and transaction-processing variants.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-database] Oracle products follow a custom release-numbering and -naming convention.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-database] The "ai" in the current release, Oracle AI Database 26ai, stands for "Artificial Intelligence".
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-database] Oracle Database 19c, 10g, and Oracle9i Database) have used suffixes of "c", "g", and "i" which stand for "Cloud", "Grid", and "Internet" respectively.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-database] Prior to the release of Oracle8i Database, no suffixes featured in Oracle AI Database naming conventions.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-database] There was no v1 of Oracle AI Database, as Ellison "knew no one would want to buy version 1".
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-database] For some database releases, Oracle also provides an Express Edition (XE) that is free to use.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-database] The Introduction to Oracle AI Database includes a brief history on some of the key innovations introduced with each major release of Oracle AI Database.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-database] See My Oracle Support (MOS) note *Release Schedule of Current Database Releases (Doc ID 742060.1)* for the current Oracle AI Database releases and their patching end dates.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-database] Prior to Oracle Database 18c, Oracle Corporation released Critical Patch Updates (CPUs) and Security Patch Updates (SPUs) and Security Alerts to close security vulnerabilities.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-database] These releases are issued quarterly; some of these releases have updates issued prior to the next quarterly release.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-database] Starting with Oracle Database 18c, Oracle Corporation releases Release Updates (RUs) and Release Update Revisions (RURs).
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-database] RUs usually contain security, regression (bug), optimizer, and functional fixes which may include feature extensions as well.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-database] RURs include all fixes from their corresponding RU but only add new security and regression fixes.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/oracle-database] However, no new optimizer or functional fixes are included.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] A **virtual private network** (**VPN**) is an overlay network that uses network virtualization to extend a private network across a public network, such as the Internet, via the use of encryption and tunneling protocols.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] In a VPN, a tunneling protocol is used to transfer network messages from one network host to another.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Host-to-network VPNs are commonly used by organizations to allow off-site users secure access to an office network over the Internet.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Site-to-site VPNs connect two networks, such as an office network and a datacenter.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Provider-provisioned VPNs isolate parts of the provider's own network infrastructure in virtual segments, in ways that make the contents of each segment private with respect to the others.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Individuals also use VPNs to encrypt and attempt to anonymize their network traffic, with VPN services selling access to their own private networks.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] VPNs can enhance usage privacy by making an ISP unable to access the private data exchanged across the VPN.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] However, the VPN provider and the online service being accessed via the VPN may have visibility of the user's activities.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Through encryption, VPNs enhance confidentiality and reduce the risk of successful external data sniffing attacks.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] A network is a group of communicating computers known as hosts, which communicate data to other hosts via communication protocols, as facilitated by networking hardware.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Within a computer network, computers are identified by network addresses, which allow rule-based systems such as Internet Protocol (IP) to locate and identify hosts.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Hosts may also have hostnames, memorable labels for the host nodes, which are rarely changed after initial assignment.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] The transmission medium that supports information exchange includes wired media like copper cables, optical fibers, and wireless radio-frequency media.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] The arrangement of hosts and hardware within a network architecture is known as the network topology.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] A communication protocol is a set of rules for exchanging information over a network.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Communication protocols have various characteristics, such as being connection-oriented or connectionless, or using circuit switching or packet switching.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] In a protocol stack, often constructed per the OSI model, communications functions are divided into protocol layers, where each layer leverages the services of the layer below it until the lowest layer controls the hardware that sends information across the media.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] The use of protocol layering is ubiquitous across the field of computer networking.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] An important example of a protocol stack is HTTP, the World Wide Web protocol.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] HTTP runs over TCP over IP, the internet protocols, which in turn run over IEEE 802.11, the Wi-Fi protocol.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] This stack is used between a wireless router and a personal computer when accessing the web.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Most modern computer networks use protocols based on packet-mode transmission.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] A network packet is a formatted unit of data carried by a packet-switched network.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Packets consist of two types of data: control information and user data (payload).
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] The control information provides data the network needs to deliver the user data, for example, source and destination network addresses, error detection codes, and sequencing information.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Typically, control information is found in packet headers and trailers, with payload data in between.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] The Internet protocol suite, also called TCP/IP, is the foundation of all modern networking and the defining set of protocols for the Internet.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] It offers connection-less and connection-oriented services over an inherently unreliable network traversed by datagram transmission using Internet protocol (IP).
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] At its core, the protocol suite defines the addressing, identification, and routing specifications for Internet Protocol Version 4 (IPv4) and for IPv6, the next generation of the protocol with a much enlarged addressing capability.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] VPNs do not make connected users anonymous or unidentifiable to the untrusted medium network provider, such as an Internet service provider (ISP).
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] However, VPNs can enhance usage privacy by making an ISP unable to access the private data exchanged across the VPN.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Through encryption, VPNs enhance confidentiality and reduce the risk of successful data sniffing attacks.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Data packets travelling across a VPN may also be secured by tamper proofing via a message authentication code, prevents the message from being altered or tampered without being rejected, enhancing data integrity.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] A number of other implementations exist to ensure authentication of connecting parties.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Tunnel endpoints can be authenticated in various ways during the VPN access initiation, such as by the whitelisting of endpoint IP address.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Authentication may also occur after actual tunnels are already active, for example, with a web captive portal.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Remote-access VPNs may also use passwords, biometrics, two-factor authentication, or other cryptographic methods.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Site-to-site VPNs often use passwords (pre-shared keys) or digital certificates.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Split tunneling allows a user to access distinct security domains at the same time, using the same or different network connections.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] This connection state is usually facilitated through the simultaneous use of a LAN network interface controller (NIC), radio NIC, Wireless LAN NIC, and virtual private network client software application.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Split tunneling is most commonly configured via the use of a remote-access VPN client, which allows the user to simultaneously connect to a nearby wireless network, resources on an off-site corporate network, as well as websites over the Internet.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Advantages of split tunneling include alleviating bottlenecks, conserving bandwidth (as Internet traffic does not have to pass through the VPN server), and enabling a user to not have to continually connect and disconnect when remotely accessing resources..
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Disadvantages include DNS leaks and potentially bypassing gateway-level security that might be in place within the company infrastructure.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Internet service providers often use split tunneling to that implement for DNS hijacking purposes.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] A *host-to-network* configuration is analogous to joining one or more computers to a network to which they cannot be directly connected.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] This type of extension provides computer access to a local area network of a remote site, or any wider enterprise networks, such as an intranet.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Each computer is in charge of activating its own tunnel towards the network it wants to join.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] The joined network is only aware of a single remote host for each tunnel.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] This may be employed for remote workers, or to enable people accessing their private home or company resources without exposing them on the public Internet.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] A *site-to-site* configuration connects two networks.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] This configuration expands a network across geographically disparate locations.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Tunneling is only done between gateway devices located at each network location.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] These devices then make the tunnel available to other local network hosts that aim to reach any host on the other side.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] This is useful to keep sites connected to each other in a stable manner, like office networks to their headquarters or datacenter.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] In this case, any side may be configured to initiate the communication as long as it knows how to reach the other.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] In the context of site-to-site configurations, the terms *intranet* and *extranet* are used to describe two different use cases.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] An *intranet* site-to-site VPN describes a configuration where the sites connected by the VPN belong to the same organization, whereas an *extranet* site-to-site VPN joins sites belonging to multiple organizations.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] A limitation of traditional VPNs is that they are point-to-point connections and do not tend to support broadcast domains.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Therefore, communication, software, and networking that are based on layer 2 and broadcast packets (such as NetBIOS used in Windows networking) may not be fully supported as on a local area network.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Variants on VPN such as Virtual Private LAN Service (VPLS) and layer 2 tunneling protocols are designed to overcome this limitation.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Trusted VPNs do not use cryptographic tunneling; instead, they rely on the security of a single provider's network to protect the traffic.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS) often overlays trusted VPNs, often with quality-of-service control over a trusted delivery network.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] A secure VPN either trusts the underlying delivery network or enforces security with an internal mechanism.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Unless the trusted delivery network runs among physically secure sites only, both trusted and secure models need an authentication mechanism for users to gain access to the VPN.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Mobile VPNs are widely used in public safety where they give law-enforcement officers access to applications such as computer-assisted dispatch and criminal databases, and in other organizations with similar requirements such as field service management and healthcare.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Dynamic Multipoint Virtual Private Network (DMVPN) is a dynamic tunneling form of a virtual private network supported on Cisco IOS-based routers, Huawei AR G3 routers, and Unix-like operating systems.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] DMVPN provides the capability for creating a dynamic-mesh VPN network without having to statically pre-configure all possible tunnel end-point peers, such as IPsec and ISAKMP peers.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] DMVPN is initially configured to build a hub-and-spoke network by statically configuring the hubs (VPN headends) on the spokes; no change in the configuration on the hub is required to accept new spokes.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Using this initial hub-and-spoke network, tunnels between spokes are dynamically built on demand without additional configuration on the hubs or spokes.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] This dynamic-mesh capability alleviates the need for any load on the hub to route data between the spoke networks.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Ethernet VPN (EVPN) is a technology for carrying OSI layer 2 Ethernet traffic as a virtual private network using wide area network protocols.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS) is a routing technique in telecommunications networks that directs data from one node to the next based on labels rather than network addresses.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Whereas network addresses identify endpoints, MPLS labels identify established paths between endpoints.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] MPLS can encapsulate packets of various network protocols.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] In practice, MPLS is mainly used to forward IP protocol data units and Virtual Private LAN Service Ethernet traffic.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Major applications of MPLS are telecommunications traffic engineering and MPLS VPN.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Virtual Private LAN Service (VPLS) is a virtual private network technology that provides Ethernet-based multipoint-to-multipoint communication over IP or MPLS networks.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] It allows geographically dispersed sites to share an Ethernet broadcast domain by connecting sites (including both servers and clients) through pseudowires.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] The technologies that can be used as pseudo-wire can be Ethernet over MPLS, L2TPv3 or even GRE.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] There are two IETF standards-track RFCs (RFC 4761 and RFC 4762) describing VPLS establishment.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] In contrast to L2TPv3, which allows only point-to-point OSI layer 2 tunnels, VPLS allows any-to-any (multipoint) connectivity.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] A virtual private network is based on a tunneling protocol, and may be combined with other network or application protocols to provide additional security and capabilities.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Internet Protocol Security (IPsec) is a standards-based security protocol, initially developed by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) for IPv6, and was required in all standards-compliant implementations of IPv6 before RFC 6434 made it only a recommendation.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] The design of IPSec meets most security goals: availability, integrity, and confidentiality.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] IPsec uses encryption, encapsulating an IP packet inside an IPsec packet.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] De-encapsulation happens at the end of the tunnel, where the original IP packet is decrypted and forwarded to its intended destination.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] IPsec is also often supported by network hardware accelerators, which makes IPsec VPN desirable for low-power scenarios, like always-on remote access VPN configurations.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] IPsec tunnels are set up by the Internet Key Exchange (IKE) protocol.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] IPsec tunnels made with IKE version 1 (also known as IKEv1 tunnels, or often just "IPsec tunnels") can be used alone to provide VPN but are often combined with the Layer 2 Tunneling Protocol (L2TP) to reuse existing L2TP-related implementations for more flexible authentication features (e.g.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] IKE version 2, which was created by Microsoft and Cisco, can be used alone to provide IPsec VPN functionality.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Its primary advantages are the native support for authenticating via the Extensible Authentication Protocol (EAP) and that the tunnel can be seamlessly restored when the IP address of the associated host is changing, which is typical of a roaming mobile device, whether on 3G or 4G LTE networks.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Transport Layer Security (SSL/TLS) can tunnel an entire network's traffic (as it does in the OpenVPN project and SoftEther VPN project) or secure an individual connection.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] A number of vendors provide remote-access VPN capabilities through TLS.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] A VPN based on TLS can connect from locations where the usual TLS web navigation (HTTPS) is supported without requiring additional configuration.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] OpenSSH offers VPN tunneling (distinct from port forwarding) to secure remote connections to a network, inter-network links, and remote systems.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] OpenSSH server provides a limited number of concurrent tunnels.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] The VPN feature itself does not support personal authentication.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] SSH is more often used to remotely connect to machines or networks instead of a site to site VPN connection.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] OpenVPN is a free and open-source VPN protocol based on the TLS protocol.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] It supports perfect forward-secrecy, and most modern secure cipher suites, like AES, Serpent, TwoFish, etc.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] It is currently being developed and updated by OpenVPN Inc., a non-profit providing secure VPN technologies.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Secure Socket Tunneling Protocol (SSTP) is a form of VPN tunnel that provides a mechanism to transport Point-to-Point Protocol (PPP) traffic through an SSL/TLS channel.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] WireGuard is a protocol designed to be more lightweight than OpenVPN.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] In 2020, WireGuard support was added to both the Linux and Android kernels, opening it up to adoption by VPN providers.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] By default, WireGuard utilizes the Curve25519 protocol for key exchange and ChaCha20-Poly1305 for encryption and message authentication, but also includes the ability to pre-share a symmetric key between the client and server.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Desktop, smartphone and other end-user device operating systems usually support configuring remote access VPN from their graphical or command-line tools.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] However, due to the variety of, often non standard, VPN protocols, there exist many third-party applications that implement additional protocols not yet or no longer natively supported by the OS.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] For instance, Android lacked native IPsec IKEv2 support until version 11, and users needed to install third-party apps in order to connect that kind of VPN.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Conversely, Windows does not natively support plain IPsec IKEv1 remote access native VPN configuration (commonly used by Cisco and Fritz!Box VPN solutions).
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Network appliances, such as firewalls, often include VPN gateway functionality for either remote access or site-to-site configurations.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Their administration interfaces often facilitate setting up virtual private networks with a selection of supported protocols.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] In some cases, like in the open source operating systems devoted to firewalls and network devices (like OpenWrt, IPFire, PfSense or OPNsense), it is possible to add support for additional VPN protocols by installing missing software components or third-party apps.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Commercial appliances with VPN features based on proprietary hardware or software platforms usually support a consistent VPN protocol across their products, but do not allow customizations outside the use cases they implement.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] This is often the case for appliances that rely on hardware acceleration of VPNs to provide higher throughput or support a larger number of simultaneously connected users.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] According to a 2022 estimate, 3% of Chinese netizens use VPNs, compared to 8.5% of Americans.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] In China, VPNs are increasingly blocked and unauthorized usage can be subject to fines and legal prosecution.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Based on its estimates of leaked government documents, ChinaFile estimated in 2026 that VPN demand in China was in the low single digits.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] It also estimated that foreign apps blocked by the Great Firewall have extremely low traffic, particularly compared to domestic apps; the top five domestic apps saw traffic that was 1,000 times more than the top five foreign apps.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] As of 2025, approximately 1.75 billion people used VPNs.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] By 2027, this market is projected to grow to $76 billion.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] Amid Internet restrictions and blocking in Russia, Internet activists created the Amnezia VPN project in 2020 during a digital rights hackathon organized by Roskomsvoboda.
[src:oracle-cloud-infrastructure/virtual-private-network] The service gained popularity among Russian users by providing access to blocked resources, as well as features aimed at enhancing anonymity and resistance to traffic analysis.
